00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:45.040
NASA is working to ensure that planes avoid
one another’s wake -- and even figure out

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:46.080
how to surf them.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:51.210
With about 100,000 flights per day worldwide,
sophisticated air traffic control systems

00:00:51.210 --> 00:00:56.430
make sure planes don’t collide, but a wake
encounter can be just as dangerous.

00:00:56.430 --> 00:01:01.310
The Automated Cooperative Trajectories project
at NASA’s Armstrong Flight Research Center

00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:07.990
are using technology to track invisible, spinning
wakes described as “horizontal tornadoes”

00:01:07.990 --> 00:01:12.640
-- and they’re inspired by concepts in nature
such as when geese fly in a V-formation.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:18.420
Planes that fly on top of rising air from
wakes will be able to conserve fuel and reduce

00:01:18.420 --> 00:01:20.100
emissions.

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:21.149
Which is good.

00:01:21.149 --> 00:01:27.229
It turns out babbling babies manipulate adults
-- and it helps them further their own education.

00:01:27.229 --> 00:01:32.029
Researchers at Cornell’s Behavioral Analysis
of Beginning Years Laboratory or BABY LAB

00:01:32.029 --> 00:01:37.670
-- found that babies organize their mothers’
verbal responses and use more mature babbling

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:40.140
to draw out more interaction.

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:45.010
That results in a greater number of learning
opportunities for babies and encourages simpler

00:01:45.010 --> 00:01:47.679
responses and learnable information.

00:01:47.679 --> 00:01:52.529
So blahblahblah actually means... teach me
more.

00:01:52.529 --> 00:01:56.820
Speaking of babies, dolphins recognize themselves
in a mirror, and they can do it many months

00:01:56.820 --> 00:01:58.999
sooner than human babies.

00:01:58.999 --> 00:02:04.219
A psychologist at Hunter College spent years
working with two dolphins, Bayley and Foster,

00:02:04.219 --> 00:02:06.060
observing their behavior in a mirror.

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:11.160
She found that by 7 months, dolphins engaged
in self-directed behavior, including wagging

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:13.330
their tongues and swirling their bodies.

00:02:13.330 --> 00:02:18.510
In contrast, human babies can take 12-15 months
to reach this developmental milestone.

00:02:18.510 --> 00:02:21.610
So score one for dolphins.

00:02:21.610 --> 00:02:27.790
