00:03:43.110 --> 00:03:48.890
Mind Blow #99 in November, 2015, featured
the Scan Pyramids Project and they just recently

00:03:48.890 --> 00:03:51.370
discovered two mysterious voids.

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:55.569
The voids in the Great Pyramid of Giza will
be inspected by a mix of subatomic particle

00:03:55.569 --> 00:03:57.760
detection and tiny robots.

00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:02.870
Built over 4,500 years ago, the Great Pyramid
is the oldest Wonder of the World but it’s

00:04:02.870 --> 00:04:05.150
difficult to study without damaging.

00:04:05.150 --> 00:04:10.010
Small particles called muons form when cosmic
rays interact with the Earth’s atmosphere,

00:04:10.010 --> 00:04:13.220
and they lose speed when they travel through
dense objects.

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:18.100
By measuring muon velocity, they identified
two secret chambers that could be corridors,

00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:21.530
serve structural functions, or… who knows.

00:04:21.530 --> 00:04:25.780
A team from the French National Institute
for Computer Science and Applied Mathematics

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:30.850
is also constructing two very small robots
that will be able to explore the voids by

00:04:30.850 --> 00:04:33.950
entering through a tiny drilled hole.

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:39.280
A team of Canadian paleontologists have shed
light on why few modern animals have the tail

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:42.000
weaponry that made some dinosaurs so destructive.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.570
They concluded that animals with tail weapons
like the ankylosaurus were generally large,

00:04:47.570 --> 00:04:50.130
herbivorous, and had armored bodies.

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:54.810
As skin armor evolved from bone, tail weapons
evolved to be softer, too.

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:59.800
Modern animals like porcupines tend to have
tail weapons made of the softer keratin -- except

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:05.210
for Smaug, a small lizard named after the
dragon in The Hobbit that retains a bony,

00:05:05.210 --> 00:05:06.880
spiked tail.

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:09.250
Presumably to guard treasure.

00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:14.090
The Coyote III, initially designed for space
exploration, is now being used for search

00:05:14.090 --> 00:05:17.400
and rescue and to identify gas leaks in buildings.

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:21.750
The German Research Center for Artificial
Intelligence developed the Coyote and proved

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:25.060
that it was capable of handling any kind of
terrain.

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:30.680
Its on-board computer allows autonomous exploration
and responding to data from sensors for practical

00:05:30.680 --> 00:05:35.680
purposes here on Earth -- yet another trickle-down
benefit from space research.

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:39.670
Roosters are really loud why don’t they
go deaf?

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:44.150
Roosters have evolved to protect themselves
from their own deafening crows.

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:47.790
Researchers at the University of Antwerp and
University of Ghent found that the internal

00:05:47.790 --> 00:05:53.790
sound pressure of a rooster’s crow can reach
a whopping 140 decibels, which is 50 decibels

00:05:53.790 --> 00:05:57.669
more than a lawn mower and 20 more than a
loud concert.

00:05:57.669 --> 00:06:02.330
Micro-CT scans of roosters’ heads showed
that their auditory canal closes when their

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:08.480
beak opens, which essentially plugs their
own ears and insulates them from damage.

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:09.650
Now you know that.

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:14.140
The brains of musicians may be as different
as the music they play.

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:18.200
Researchers from the Max Planck Institute
for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences in

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:23.169
Liepzig found that different processes occur
in the brains of classical and jazz musicians

00:06:23.169 --> 00:06:25.889
even when they played the exact same piece.

00:06:25.889 --> 00:06:29.900
The study of professional pianists showed
that jazz musicians were more flexible and

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:35.250
able to “re-plan” harmonies more easily
than classical pianists, suggesting that evaluating

00:06:35.250 --> 00:06:40.020
the effects of music on the brain might be
most accurate when done across the global

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:41.280
musical spectrum.

